sses (Coulomb scattering, Compton scattering, and bremsstrahlung). These processes are related to other phenomena, such as pair production, and the comparisons are discussed. A unique feature of the book is its thorough discussion of the nonrelativistic limit of QED, which is simpler than the relativistic theory in its formulation and applications. The methods of the relativistic theory are introduced and applied through the use of notions of covariance, to provide a shorter path to the more general theory. The book will be useful for graduate students working in astrophysics and in certain areas of particle physics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aElectromagnetic theory. 0aNonrelativistic quantum mechanics. 0aQuantum electrodynamics. 0aScattering (Physics). 7aSCIENCE / Physics / Electromagnetism.2bisacsh  aBohr radius.  aClassical Electrodynamics.  aCompton effect.  aCompton wavelength.  aDirac equation.  aHamiltonian.  aLagrangian.  aMaxwell equations.  aPrinciple of Relativity.  aRydberg energy.  aangular distributions.  aatomic size.  achannels for reactions.  acovariance.  adensity transformation.  afields of a moving charge.  agauge invariance.  aintermediate-state photons.  ainvariant flux.  aphase-space volume.  aphoton concept.  areduced mass.  aretarded potentials.  ascattering amplitude.  aspin sums.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691215846zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691215846423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691215846.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MTPY  aEBA